66","about 1363":"about 1363","1392":"1392","Castle Knock, Camus Castle), Armadale, County West Lothian Scotland":"Scotland","Ireland":"Ireland","Rodel, Harris, Inverness, Scotland":"Rodel, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Dunvegan, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Dunvegan, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Dunvegan Castle, Isle of Skye, County Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Dunvegan, Inverness-shire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"O'Neil","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Conn, Donal, Liam, Siobhan, Aileen, Eamon, Michael Patrick, Seamus, Sean Patrick, William Sean.","Irish (Mayo, Tipperary): variant of   O'Neill  ."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Neill","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Seamus, Siobhan, Dermot, Liam, Nuala, Bridie, Brigid, Conor, Fintan, John Patrick.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Néill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Niall</i>’, an Irish personal name possibly derived from <i>néal</i> ‘cloud’ (see   Neil  ).","History: Bearers of this surname mostly claim descent from Niall Noígíallach (Niall of the Nine Hostages), a legendary king of Ireland who flourished in the 5th century. His descendants, the Ui Neill dynasty, dominated Ireland, on and off, from the 6th to the 10th century. The surname itself can be traced with some confidence to one of these descendants, namely Niall Glúndubh mac Aodha (died 919), High King of Ireland from 911 to 919, with a power base in Tyrone, Ulster."]}]},{"name":"Annie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."],"variants":[{"name":"Anni","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]},{"name":"Anne","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Annie O'Neil was born in 1340, in Ireland. She married John, Ian Ciar MacLeod 4th. Clan Chief before 1355, in Dunvegan, Inverness-shire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1450, in Scotland, at the age of 110."},"et":{"1340–1450":"1340–1450","1330–1392":"1330–1392","1355–1402":"1355–1402","1363–Male":"1363–Surnud","1366–Female":"1366–Surnud","1402":"1402","before 1355":"enne 1355","1355":"1355","1366":"1366","1363":"1363","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1450":"1450","about 1366":"umbes 1366","about 1363":"umbes 1363","1392":"1392","Castle Knock, Camus Castle), Armadale, County West Lothian Scotland":"Scotland","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Rodel, Harris, Inverness, Scotland":"Rodel, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Dunvegan, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Dunvegan, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Dunvegan Castle, Isle of Skye, County Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Dunvegan, Inverness-shire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1340–1450":"1340–1450","1330–1392":"1330–1392","1355–1402":"1355–1402","1363–Male":"1363–Kuollut","1366–Female":"1366–Kuollut","1402":"1402","before 1355":"ennen vuotta 1355","1355":"1355","1366":"1366","1363":"1363","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1450":"1450","about 1366":"noin 1366","about 1363":"noin 1363","1392":"1392","Castle Knock, Camus Castle), Armadale, County West Lothian Scotland":"Scotland","Ireland":"Irlanti","Rodel, Harris, Inverness, Scotland":"Rodel, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Dunvegan, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Dunvegan, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Dunvegan Castle, Isle of Skye, County Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Dunvegan, Inverness-shire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1340–1450":"1340–1450","1330–1392":